    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">ᚃᚑᚈᚔ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">VOTI</name></persName>
                </ab>
               <!-- <ab type="list"></ab>-->
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>An o in Ogham may be short or long, so the form could be the genitive of a personal name VŎTAS or VŌTAS.</note>                   
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'of Foth?'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>VŎTAS would correspond to an Old Irish o-stem <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/24153">Foth</ref></distinct>, and VŌTAS to an Old Irish o-stem <distinct xml:lang="sga">Fúath</distinct> (earlier <distinct xml:lang="pgl">Fóth</distinct>). No such names have been identified in manuscript sources. The Latin personal name <persName xml:lang="la">Votus</persName> is rare, and not attested in Irish contexts. </p>
            </div>
